{
  "text": "Postdeposition Effects. In addition to climatic factors we also examined the possible influence of postdeposition effects on the water isotopic composition. If wind-driven snow removal were the main factor of the \u03b4 18 O variation, the same correlation between \u03b4 18 O and 17 O-excess as in seasonal event-based data should be preserved in the interannual data, because when the snow mixes, its compounds mix in the same way. Because an anticorrelation between \u03b4 18 O and 17 O-excess has been observed in the snow pit data, the only remaining postdeposition process to be taken into account is isotopic fractionation in the firn. Diffusion of water molecules has been shown to affect the record of water isotopic profiles in Greenland [CITATION_1] O-excess is to invoke the situation where the precipitated snow is partly sublimated (here 20%) at a relatively high temperature T subl (here \u221220\u00b0C) and condensed again onto the snow pack at a lower temperature T cond (here \u221255\u00b0C). Observations showed that sublimation (as high as 10-20% of the total precipitation) mainly happens in December and January, when the air temperature is between \u221215\u00b0C and \u221230\u00b0C. Taking into account the associated fractionation (SI Text), sublimation and subsequent condensation of snow would lead to an increase of \u03b4 18 O (+2.1\u2030), which is in antiphase with the resulting decrease of d-excess (\u22122.8\u2030) and 17 O-excess (\u221243 ppm) ( Table 1) . On the basis of the numbers in Table 1 , assuming an extreme case of postdepositional sublimation and recondensation, relatively high \u03b4 18 O would still correspond to relatively high 17 Oexcess. Furthermore, strong sublimation effects have been reported for sites with strong katabatic winds and for relatively high temperatures [CITATION_2] , whereas Vostok is marked by very low temperatures and moderate wind speed (13) . In addition, an experiment was performed to look at the isotopic evolution of the Vostok snow when it is exposed to relatively dry conditions. The snow isotopic composition evolved with an increase in both \u03b4 18 O and 17 O-excess at the end of the experiment. Therefore, postdeposition effects cannot explain the changed relationship between \u03b4 18 O and 17 O-excess from the correlation that is observed on the seasonal scale (where postdeposition effects can be excluded) to the anticorrelation that is observed on the interannual scale.",
  "citation_candidates": [
